ce:section.ce:para:
Geometry optimization of graphene doped surface and gas molecules in this study was done using the B3LYP functional with empirical dispersion (GD3BJ) at 6-311+G (d, p) level of theory. The employed empirical dispersion is suitable to predict weak intermolecular interactions. From previous Studies, high adsorption properties of graphene quantum dots are due to its surface area [33]. Graphene surface consist of a single layer arranged in a two-dimensional lattice and comprises of 36 carbon atoms which are surrounded with hydrogen atoms, this gives it the highest number of edge atoms in comparison to another allotrope [34]. Atoms at the edges of a graphene have special chemical reactivity which makes graphene surface suitable for adsorption studies [35]. As reported in literatures, Doping is said to improve the adsorption characteristics of nanomaterials [30]. Herein, N and S doped atom confirms it effect on graphene quantum dot surface for adsorbing; C2H4, CH4 and H2 gases. Nitrogen (N) and sulfur (S) atoms were doped on graphene quantum dots and was achieved by substituting a C atom in the central ring of the surface and this gives it two possible sites for adsorptions [9]. The possible sites for adsorption on graphene doped with N, S atom are; the site at the middle of a CC bond and on the doped atom in the central ring. Previous report by Ganji et al. [36], that doped Pt atom on the bridge site (middle of a CC bond) is more stable than the two other positions. Thus, site of doped atom is best for potential adsorption. Mohsen et al. [37], also reported that sites for doped atom are stable and suitable for adsorptions. The optimized geometries of three gas molecules C2H4, CH4 and H2 are presented in Fig. 1
                        . The C–H bond of C2H4 is 1.070 Å, compared with that of CH4 (1.090 Å), this is due to hybridization effect of CH4 (sp3
                        ) compared to that of C2H4 (sp2
                        ) with stronger electronegativity of carbon atom in C2H4. This result is in agreement with previous study by Gui et al.20 [16]. After adsorption CH bonds for CH4 and C2H4 were observed to be (1.096 Å and 1.085 Å) and is similar to that reported by Rad and close to published experimental data [9,36]. For HH bond before adsorption bond length observed was 1.074 Å and increased to 1.777 Å after optimization. simulated results for bond lengths infers differences in observed results. Bond lengths for doped surface between C-N and C-S bonds were 1.408 Å and 1.770 Å, doped atoms were strain above the flat six-membered rings. However, the morphology of the dopants changed and their adsorption properties increased. To obtain stable configurations for gases on doped surface for C2H4, hydrogen atom on the left end is posed with substituted atoms on graphene quantum dot surface. In the case of CH4, one hydrogen atom placed on the right was also posed with doped atoms. Finally, H atom at the right end is posed on doped atoms on graphene surface.

Insights from Barder's theory, [54] topological parameters; electron density ρ(r), Lagrangian kinetic energy G(r), Hamiltonian kinetic energy K(r), Potential energy density V(r), Electron energy density H(r), and the Laplacian density ▾2ρ(r) and Bond ellipticity ε, at bond critical points (BCPs) were investigated and computed in Table 3
                        . for all adsorptions. The electron density p(r) and its Laplacian ▾2ρ(r) allow the nature of the interactions to be determined. In general, large values of ▾2ρ(r) and p(r) indicate that hydrogen interactions are quite strong [55]. The electron density p(r) is essential in values where ▾2ρ(r) is negative, and it also displays the charge concentration for all adsorptions except GQD_N_C2H4 adsorption with positive value for ▾2ρ(r) (0.135) this suggests charge distribution within adsorbing surface and adsorbate. Bond ellipticity, ε, is a valuable term that is important in the description of structural instability in adsorptions [56]. Larger values of ε (i.e., ε > 1) indicate structural instability and lower values for ε is attributed to the structural stability of the adsorption (i.e., ε < 1) [57]. For all adsorptions smaller values for ε which falls between (0.008 and −1.226) entails stability upon adsorption of studied gases on GQD_N & GQD_S surface. This result is similar to that reported by Doust et al. for BNAINS and BNGaNS surface for the adsorption of 1-Chloro-1,2,2,2-Tetrafluoroethane [58]. The results reported in Table 3. indicate that, there is a remarkable intermolecular interaction between the substituted nitrogen atom and the carbon atom in the central ring of the adsorbing surface (Graphene) and a notable intramolecular interaction between carbon and hydrogen atoms between rings in graphene. Purely ionic interaction is observed due to small ρ(r) values, 0.018 – 0.295 for GQD_N and 0.287- 0.432 for GQD_S. Moreover, when G(r)/|V|(r) < 0.5 the nature of the adsorption is covalent, and if G(r)/|V|(r) >1, the adsorption is non-covalent [59]. CH4 adsorption on GQD_N with 0.251 is covalent, whereas C2H4 (1.355) and H2 (2.433) adsorption on GQD_N are non-covalent. Adsorption of C2H4 on the GQD_S surface is covalent for C33-C54 (1.069) and non-covalent for C13-H55 (G(r)/V(r) 0.5). (0.250). Bonds between C27-H55 (1.371) and C4-C17 (2.415) are reported to be covalent for CH4 adsorption on GP_S, but bonds between C8-H54 are non-covalent with G(r)/V(r) < 0.5. (0.245). Finally, bonds between C27 – H53 – H44 and C4 – H53 with G(r)/|V|(r) values >1 (2.461 & 1.360) are said to be covalent, whereas bonds between C8 – C32 – H53 with G(r)/V(r) < 0.5 (0.249) are stated to be non-covalent after H2 adsorption on GQD_S. As a result of the reduced values ε upon adsorption, stability is achieved for studied surfaces. Thus GQD_S and GQD_N are suitable adsorbents for C2H4, CH4 and H2 gases (Fig. 5
                        ).
